1 WHEREAS, that iconic home run was Morris's only home run of the 1996 season,
2 as he had previously suffered a broken hamate bone in his right wrist and missed thirty-nine
3 games following surgery before returning late in the season to help lead LSU to the
4 championship; and
5 WHEREAS, the historic moment and the story of Morris's perseverance and triumph
6 have been chronicled by ESPN as part of the acclaimed Southeastern Conference storied
7 episode titled "The Walk Off", highlighting the significance of his accomplishment within
8 the tradition of Southeastern Conference athletics; and
9 WHEREAS, Morris began his collegiate career at LSU as a walk-on after graduating
10 from Bolton High School, initially redshirting and transitioning from the outfield to second
11 base; and
12 WHEREAS, during his sophomore season, Morris emerged as one of the top players
13 in the conference, earning second-team All-American and All-SEC honors after leading LSU
14 in batting average (.369), runs scored (70), hits (93), stolen bases (18), and on-base
15 percentage (.481), and earning first-team Academic All-American recognition; and
16 WHEREAS, he was selected to represent the United States on the United States
17 national baseball team in 1995, finishing third on the team in batting average and
18 demonstrating exceptional leadership as the leadoff hitter; and
19 WHEREAS, despite injury challenges during his junior season, Morris returned to
20 help LSU dominate late in the year, as the Tigers compiled a perfect 22-0 record in games
21 he started in 1996 and he led the team in hitting during the NCAA Tournament with a .433
22 average; and
23 WHEREAS, Morris later represented the United States in the 1996 Summer
24 Olympics, where he led the team in batting with a .409 average and helping Team USA
25 capture the bronze medal; and
26 WHEREAS, following his collegiate career, Morris was selected in the fifth round
27 of the 1996 Major League Baseball Draft by the Texas Rangers and he later made his Major
28 League debut in 1999 with the Pittsburgh Pirates, finishing third in voting for National
29 League Rookie of the Year Award after batting .288 with fifteen home runs and
30 seventy-three runs batted in; and
